 of web development. Even the most seasoned developers <a class="outside-link" href="https://davidwalsh.name/impostor-syndrome" target="_blank">still feel like imposters sometimes.</a></p> <p>My goal here is to make front-end development as approachable as possible. However, please keep in mind most of the tutorials here are not geared for the complete novice. They assume you know at least a little bit about HTML, CSS, and JavaScript. If you don't, don't give up yet. I highly recommend you head over to <a class="outside-link" href="https://www.codecademy.com" target="_blank">Codecademy</a> and start there, beginning with their easy to follow introductory courses to HTML and CSS, and then proceed to JavaScript.</p <hr> <h1>How I Arrived Here</h1> <p>My path to arriving at a career in web development was as unconvential as one could possible imagine. I don't have a computer science degree, but I do have a college degree...in business administration. Before becoming a front-end developer I bounced around in all sorts of industries - from a car rental agency, to business loan officer, to customer service, to merchandising, to retail. After an early onset mid-life crisis in 2015, I decided it was time to make a major change in my life, and decided to try my hand at web development, something I had been genuinely curious about for many years. I learned enough over the course of six months to be dangerous via <a class="outside-link" href="https://www.thinkful.com" target="_blank">Thinkful</a>, with the assistance of a great mentor, <a class="outside-link" href="https://devries.jp" target="_blank">J.P. DeVries</a>, and secured my first job in the summer of 2016.</p> </article> <footer class="site-footer"> <div class="container"> <ul class="social"> <li><a href="http://github.com/bpcoxjr" target="_blank"><i class="icon icon-github"></i></a></li> <li><a href="http://linkedin.com/in/bpcoxjr" target="_blank"><i class="icon icon-linkedin"></i></a></li> <li><a href="http://twitte